Item_Response: James Fort            In 1994, historians began the Jamestown Rediscovery Archeology Project.  For 200 years people think that James Fort in Jamestown, Virginia had been washed away by a river. Because of some discoveries mad that might just be a myth.               James Fort was built in 1607 when settlers or people came from England. You can see that in 1994 it would be had to recover these interesting artifacts. Not just historians but other people thought that it was built near a river, but objects that were found were in fact not at all close to the river. So these people figured that it would give more protection when enemy ships were near.            The first objects found was not even in this century. They were found in 1861. Item_Response: Digging Up History                                                       By Brooke Corbett           I chose learning about the job of an archeologist and how they find or dig up history.   Many of history's mystery's are solved by archeologists. Their job is to find artifacts about how was it like in the past. One of their amazing discovery's they found was about George Washington and Fort James.       We all know about George Washington as a solider and a President but what about his childhood? Archeologists are finding more about Washington's childhood everyday. As we know it George lived on the property now know as Ferry Farm. His family moved there when he was just six years old. Four other houses have been build on Ferry Farm. Archeologists found burnt pottery in one of the houses, they are suggesting a fire might of occurred in the house. Along with the burnt pottery they found a clay pipe. We knew that Washington had smoked on a pipe. Now they know that this was Washington's House! We need to know about out ancestors in the past to build new items that can help us with the world today.       Now during that whole process of finding burnt pottery and Washington's clay pipe their is a team all behind it. Thirty-five people can be on a team and five teams each have work to do. The firsts team maps out  the area to see whats underground and what the artifacts on a 3D computer. The second team does the digging that is called a dig. This archeologist team uses skim shovels. Skim shovels are small, flat and sharp. Skim shovels are used to remove thin layers of soil. Each layer of soil goes in a small box with 1/2 of a screen at the bottom. The dirt falls out and if your lucky you can find a artifact.       Diggers also use another process or technique called troweling.The archeologists use paintbrushes. wooden picks and small shovels for troweling.When they are troweling it could take them up to two weeks to trowel a twenty-five-square foot section. Then another archeologist team is in a lab to find out what this artifact was used for and what can it do to help us in the modern world? Its a very long process but after all that hard work its worth it! Also architects use modern shovels, and a whisk and dustpan. you never know if your standing right on a artifact! Archeologists also use a knife to scrape of dirt off artifacts. Wheelbarrows are also useful for carrying dirt or artifacts.       Archeologists found another interesting artifacts at Fort James in Jamestown, Virginia, For over two hundred years people thought it had been washed away by the Pacific's ocean by its strong current and waves. But archeologists believe that there still might be some remains of the Fort. Fort James was built in 1607 where the settlers came to separate from England and start a new life. No wonder why they chose to set up a fort there. It was easy to dock ships, they thought the fort was located near the dock but near by artifacts that it was farther away that probably was a good idea so they could be hidden and protected by nearby or enemy ships. The items that indicate that it was farther away was in 1861 now about a hundred years later they started the search again.       After a five year study and learning how the land was used by National Park services they finally found Fort James! They set up pegs on the ground to show how big the fort was. With all the rumors, books, and drawings the archeologists made they found out the fort was shaped like a triangle. They also found out the top of the buildings ledges were for cannons. The archeologist also found that there were dozens of burial sites and ten buildings near Fort James. Each year the archeologists found a total of a million artifacts. They found tools, armor, weapons, coins, pottery even metal toys! This place was a natural gold mine for architects!       Today its very exciting to learn how people were back then. How they lived and survived through the night. How their childhood was or how they kept safe from enemies! Isn't it amazing how we are finding more and more about history everyday! Archeologist are looking for more historic artifacts today. Not just in the United States. There is still millions of artifacts that are needed to be found! So maybe when your older you can join the hunt!

Item_Response: Archeologists                                             By Sarah Hoskin        An archeologist is a person who studies objects from the past. Archeologists find objects by digging. First the archeloogists map the site where they will be digging using 3D computers. The place where they dig is called a dig. Next the archeologists start digging.  They start digging with small, flat, sharp shovels that can remove thin layers of soil one at a time. These shovels are called skim shovels. Next the archeologists put the soil in a box with a screen in the  bottom. The soil goes through the screen but the artifacts stay in the box. Next the archeologists remove dirt from the objects. The artifacts go to a lab where another team of archeologists study them.        Archeologists use many tools to do their job. These tools are a pick and shovel, a whisk and dustpan, a knife, a wheelbarrow, a skim shovel, and a trowel. A pick and shovel are used to dig close to the artifacts. A whisk and dustpan are used to brush dirt off the artifacts. A knife is used to scrape dirt off the artifacts. A wheelbarrow is used to move things and dirt from one place to another. A skim shovel is used to remove a layer of soil wiht each scoop and a trowel is used to cut the soil to view different layers of soil.        Archeologists help us learn about the past and how peopole in the past lived. They also help us learn more about the lives of famous peopole that lived in the past. Being an archeologist is a very interesting job.

Item_Response: My Report               Hello, do you won't to be an archeologist?. well if you do you would like the idea after you read this. A job of an archeologist is very fun because let me tell you that archeologist found things that were in George Washington's house years ago, but how did they find all of those things years ago. This is how. The process of digging at the Ferry Farm is a careful one.            First and foremost, Each year, many teams will work on the site. There can be up to 35 archeologist on a team! The first team maps the area using 3D computers that can track what is underground. The imformation is recorded so that people will know what it looked like before people started digging. Another team focuses on the actual digging, and the place the team does the digging is called the dig.             Secondly, Tose archeologists start their dig with what are called skim shovels. These shovels are so small, flat, and sharp that can remove thin layers of soil, one at a time. That soil is then placed in a box with a half-inch screen at the bottom. This let's the dirt fall out while the artifacts stay in. The diggers also use a process called troweling. Troweling is when archeologists use small shovels, paint brushes, and wooden picks to remove dirt.             Third, It can take up to two weeks to dig a 25-square-foot section! Another team spends days in the lab studying the objects that are found. The whole process is slow and tiresome, but it's worth it. This means that the discovery of washington's home is important for many reasons. First, it gives the citizens of the United States a better understanding of who George Washington was before he became fomous. We also begin to know why he made the decisions he did. Another thing it does is help historians learn about the type of Colonial Americans lived. All of these things are key parts of our past as Americans.             Fourth, Ferry Farm offers many opportunities for kids to get involved. The George Washington society runs summer workshops with both classroom and outdoor activities. Kids can explore the site, experience colonial life, and become junior archeologists. Kids can sign up for classes, games, and crafts. There is even an interactive website! It challenges kids to solve puzzles about the work being done at the Ferry Farm.              Fifth, The tools that archeoloigists use are the Pick and the Shovel, the Whisk and the Dustpan, The Knife, The Wheel Barrow, The Skim Shovel, and the Trowel. The Pick and the Shovel are use to start digs. they are used to dig into the earth, close to the artifact. The Whisk and the Dustpan are used to brush dirt off the artifacts and clear away dirt from the excavation site. The Knife is used for careful digging and to scrape dirt from around the artifacts. The Wheelbarrow is used to move items from one place to another or to carry dirt away from the excavation site. The Skim shovel is a shovel with a flat edge used to carefully remove a thin layer of soil wit each scoop. And the Trowel is probaly the most common tool in archeology. It is used to scrape and cut to view the different layrs of soil.             Last but not least, People have lived on the land known as the Ferry Farm for over 12,000 years. It's location makes it a perfect place to build a home. Therefore, it's not surprising that George Washington's father, Augustine Washington, moved his family there. George was just six years old at the time. No one knew exactly where the Washington home was long gone. However, archeologists believed that the stone base under the house was still there.                     Digging around in dirt can give you more than just dusty jeans. The folks at the Ferry Farm are bringing to life the country's first president in ways we have never seen.

Item_Response: Archeologists        Archeologists are people who study the past.  Archaeologists discover objects from the past, and they are scientists.  Being an archeologist takes time and patience.  Some clues are the pottery that the Americans made long ago.  You could also get clues from the trash and objects that they used!  Pottery is they most likely way to find ancient artifacts.  You could also find marks on the ground and find the place where it all began.  The artifacts that the archeologists find are important are a big part of our past.                                The way archeologists dig up the past is that they have 3 teams and they all have different jobs.  There could be up to 35 members on a team!  The first team maps the area using a 3D computer so that they can track what is underground.  Then the information is recorded so that people can know what they are looking for.             The second team starts the digging, the place the team digs at is called a dig.  The archeologists start their dig with a tool called skim shovels, which is a shovel with a flat edge used to carefully get off a thin layer of soil.  These shovels are flat, small, and sharp.  Then that soil is placed in a box with a 1/2 inch screen at the bottom.  This lets the dirt fall out and lets the artifacts stay in.             The diggers also use a process called troweling.  That is when archeologists use small shovels, paint brushes, and wooden picks to remove the dirt.  Another team spends days in the lab studying the artifacts that are found.  The reason some people stay in the lab is because that analyze the artifacts, they find out how old it is, they find out who used it, and they fin out who made it so thay can have more information on the object or person they are finding more about.              Some of the tools used by the archeologists to discover these ancient artifacts are picks and shovels which are used to dig into the earth, close to the artifacts.  A whisk and a dustpan are used to clear the dirt away from the artifacts.  A knife is used for careful digging and to scrape the dirt around the sides of the artifact.  A wheelbarrow is used to move items from one place to another or to carry dirt away from the digging site.  A skim shovel, as I explained in the other passage, is a shovel with a flat edge used to carefully remove a thin layer of soil.  A trowel is probably the most commonly used tool in archeology.  It is use to scrape and cut to view the different layers of soil.  These tools are used every day to discover the precious artifacts.            An archeologists job is long, tiresome, and hard.  They must take their time or they might miss and important clue of fact.  It can take up to two weeks to dig up a 25-square-foot section!  All of the weeks you are working adds up when you are working to dig up a large space.  It also takes up time to dig up the important information and artifacts.  Archeologists must have patience to really discover, enjoy, and appreciate the true meaning to be and archeologist.                   Without archeologists we wouldn't know anything about our past and we would be clueless about the people who came before us.  Archeologists give us proof that there were people who came before us, they give us a better understanding of what tools they used back then, and they give us a picture of what their life was like.  This is what makes the archeologist's job so amazing and interesting. What would we do without our archeologists?

Item_Response: Have you ever wanted to become an archeologists? The job has many drawbacks and exciting parts to it! However if you want the job to be quick on finding everything, then this may not be the best job for your personality. But it never is good without you trying your best! Before you become one perhaps you should know a little about this important job you are about to encounter.           Like I said before, having the job of an archeologists means that have to have lots and lots of patience. It might take perhaps a whole entire year for you to unearth a single bone or artifact! I know it does sound so terrible, however lets leave it this way. Say you are digging in a place and your quest is to look for artifacts of Abraham Lincoln. All of a sudden you touch a hard and bony thing, then you see that it is no bone but a hard and wrinkled letter from Lincoln to a close family member before his death. You have made an important discovery and you become famous! OK maybe not famous, but you have changed the world's knowledge on him forever!   You have heard the good news, but you still need patience to do this. Without patience doesn't mean that you can't do the job. You can practice having more patience. It is hard work but worth it until the end.           As a archeologists you will find lots of artifacts that are important and have not been discovered yet. There is a lot of tools that you will use to unearth artifacts to the surface, including shovels and more! This job requires a complicated list of jobs. I you even miss on it won;t be a good thing. Some of the tools include shovels to dig out stuff and be much easier than digging with your hands. Another tool is the wheelbarrow that helps you carry many things instead of going back and forth all the time! There is the whisk that helps clean fragile things and clean small narrow parts that your hand can;t reach. These are only some the tools, but soon when you have that job you will know more of the tools.           The job of an archeologists is hard bur a lot of fun to find knew things! I myself would love to become an archeologist when I grow up! It is a great job to dig up the past, and learn new things about  your home , the U.S and explore its wonders.

Item_Response: There are many artifacts yet to be found on this planet. But the question is, who is going to find it? This is the job of an archaeologist. They have to first find a location, look for the artifacts, and then transport the artifacts to scientists to see what they mean and why they are significant. A lot of tough work!                 So to even find artifacts, the archaeologists need to find where to look for. A good place would be a place that is really old, like a sixteenth century mansion, or a cave used by cavemen. After they have targeted their location, they need to get to the location and begin looking around for good places to dig and work on.             After they perfect spot is located, here comes the toughest job that may take weeks or even months. The digging is the most significant part of an archaeologist's job and life. So first, you use a trowel and a skim shovel to get the sand or ground away. Then they use the pick and shovel and start searching for artifacts. And when they hear a CLINK! they use their knife for careful digging. The hard work is complete!             Then comes the transportation. After people have taken out the artifact from the ground, light artifacts are usually given to scientists by hand. But when the artifacts are dense and heavy, archaeologists use a wheel barrow to transpot the artifacts. After the archaeologists have transported the artifacts to the scientists, the job is done!              As you can see, being an archaeologist requires a lot of work. It is not a job that can be taken by ease. But the good part is when you found the artifact and just revealed a mystery.

Item_Response: The Archeologists work !                                                                    By: Chardonnay                         In 1994 lot of people was interested in studying the past. The people that studied the past started the Jamestown Rediscovery Archaeological Project. The design was to discover the secrets and mysteries and the past of James Fort in Jamestown, Virginia. For many years, people thought that the fort had been washed away by a river. A little bit if discoveries  in the area hinted that it might still be around. The fort was built in 1607 when people came from England to begin a new life. A lot people believed that James Fort was built near the river. However, objects found nearby suggested the fort was located further away. The spot probably gave the people move protection from mean ships. The first objects were found in 1861. archeologists, the name for scientists who study things from the past. The people who study things use computer mapping software to make images of the area. That's when they finally found James Fort ! The first thing they found was a set of marks. The set of marks showed where the forts walls used to be.                 The objects include pottery, tools, coins, and even metal toys for the children. In 1600's people used to throw their trash down an unused well or into a bid pit. While digging in the area the archeologists found the trash the settlers threw away, including bones of animals ate. The information learned from these objects helps us understand how the people in James Fort lived. Now the archeologists now know how the settlers fought Powhatan tribe that often attacked them. The archeologists also know what the settlers did to survive the difficult years when they had little food.                The archeologists think it is exciting to discover objects that were regularly used by people who lived hundreds of years ago.
